[14] Virus persistence
Date: Fri 27 May 2022
Source: The Health Site [abridged, edited]
https://www.thehealthsite.com/news/monkeypox-can-linger-upto-10-weeks-in-throat-and-blood-experts-warn-of-unusual-symptoms-883223/


Monkeypox virus can stay in the blood and throat
------------------------------------------------
In a study published in the journal Lancet Infectious Diseases [reference below], experts have revealed that the monkeypox virus may persist in the body of an infected individual for up to 10 weeks, even after the tell-tale rash has disappeared.

"It remains positive in the throat and blood for the length of the illness and maybe even long after the rash," the lead author Dr Hugh Adler was quoted as saying.

Traditionally, monkeypox patients are considered infectious while they have the common symptoms of the disease, such as skin rashes and lesions, etc. However, now experts are saying that the virus may remain in the body of infected individuals even after their rashes have disappeared and scabs have fallen off.

[Byline: Satata Karmakar]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[Reference: Hugh Adler, Susan Gould, Paul Hine, Luke B Snell, Waison Wong, Catherine F Houlihan, et. Al. Clinical features and management of human monkeypox: a retrospective observational study in the UK. The Lancet Infectious Diseases. https://doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(22)00228-6

Detection of viral DNA was by PCR so presence of intact, infectious virus is unknown. This interesting report should elicit further studies on persistence of the virus in infected individuals. If infectious virus is, indeed, shed in secretions after crusts are gone, that could change the epidemiological picture and recommendations for long-term testing and isolation. - Mod.TY]

